This is a sophisticated "Hybrid" architecture. It’s essentially a brain that uses three different ways of "seeing" to understand human movement.
Here is a breakdown of the architectural components and a blueprint for your Duolingo-style ASL platform.
Part 1: The Model Architecture Breakdown
To understand the model, imagine it as a three-stage filter that processes the skeleton data.
1. The SpatialGraphConv (The "Anatomy" Expert)
Traditional AI treats video frames like flat pictures. Your model treats the body as a Graph (a web of connected points).
• How it works: It uses an adjacency matrix (the "skeleton map" we built) to understand that the "Wrist" is connected to the "Elbow," but not to the "Ankle."
• The Goal: It learns the spatial relationships. It figures out exactly where the fingers are relative to the face, which is the most critical part of ASL.
2. The MambaStyleBlock (The "Motion" Expert)
Mamba is a cutting-edge "Selective State Space" model. In your architecture, it replaces the older, slower LSTMs.
• How it works: It scans the video from start to finish. It is "selective," meaning it learns to ignore frames where the user is just standing still and focuses intensely on the specific moment the hands start to move.
• The Goal: It understands temporal flow—the "rhythm" of the sign.
3. The TransformerBlock (The "Context" Expert)
While Mamba looks at the video linearly (frame by frame), the Transformer looks at the entire video at once.
• How it works: It uses "Attention" to link the beginning of a sign to the end. For example, in the sign for "Apple," the hand starts at the cheek and twists. The Transformer ensures the model remembers the starting position while evaluating the twist.
• The Goal: Global context and consistency.
4. The Siamese Head (The "Judge")
This is the part that makes it an app. Instead of a "Classifier" (which guesses the word), the Siamese head takes the "fingerprint" (embedding) of the Teacher and the "fingerprint" of the Student and subtracts them.
• The Goal: If the difference is small, it outputs a 1 (Success). If the difference is large, it outputs a 0 (Try again).
Part 2: Structuring the App/Website
To make this work in a browser without lag, you need a specific data pipeline. You should not send raw video to your server—it's too slow and heavy.
1. The Frontend (Client-Side)
• Camera Input: The website uses the user's webcam.
• MediaPipe Integration: You use MediaPipe (JavaScript) directly in the browser. This converts the user's video into a stream of (x, y, z) coordinates in real-time.
• Data Packaging: Instead of uploading a 10MB .mp4 file, the website sends a tiny .json file containing only the skeleton coordinates to your backend.
2. The Backend (Inference Server)
• The Reference Library: You store a pre-calculated "Embedding" for every teacher video in your database. You don't need to run the model on the teacher's video every time—you do it once and save the result.
• The Comparison: 1. The backend receives the User's skeleton data.
2. It runs the User's data through your Graph_Encoder.
3. It pulls the Teacher's "Embedding" for that specific lesson from the database.
4. It passes both through the Siamese "Judge" layer.
• The Response: The server sends back a simple similarity score (e.g., 0.92).
3. The User Interface (UX)
• Live Overlay: Draw the skeleton points over the user's video in the browser so they can see if the camera is tracking them correctly.
• The Feedback Loop: * Score > 0.85: "Perfect! You've mastered 'Apple'!"
• Score 0.60 - 0.84: "So close! Try to move your hand a bit faster."
• Score < 0.60: "Oops, that doesn't look quite right. Watch the teacher again."
